olor) of the said arm.. Usually those kind of changes demand something more drastic in the scene, like the whole scene becoming darker or lighter.<br><br>I think the norm is that when the characters move their arms (or other parts of their body), the only things changing as far as light and shadow goes are the &quot;solid&quot; shadows (areas where the light doesn't reach, or where a drop shadow is cast). Coloring / animating gradients and subtle changes in shading is a tough job, even if you're doing less than 24 frames per second, so using solid shadows saves a lot of work.<br><br>And if you meant to ask how you can keep the color of an animated object constant throughout its motion (so that when viewed it doesn't look like the color is fluctuating between frames), that's easy enough on a computer. Not sure how it could be accomplished with traditional methods.. <p><hr><b>Want to color my lineart?</b> Otherwise alter something I've created? Read my <a href="http://pub25.ezboard.com/ujspuonti.showPublicProfile?language=EN"><b>profile</b></a> for further information before proceeding!</p><i></i></td></tr></table><table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showPrevMessage?topicID=3724.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showNextMessage?topicID=3724.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3724.topic&index=1><img src=http://www.polykarbon.com/bbsimage/addreply.gif border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.emailToFriend?topicID=3724.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.